    "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/decision/cou1-noncannulated-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/org/fda-cdrh-osel",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The FEA model ensemble for non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw compression-bending prediction is accepted as credible for the stated COU at MRL 5. All three primary QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) satisfy both the E/uval < 1.96 and percent difference < 10% acceptance bounds across N=11 experimental specimens from two independent laboratories. Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 credibility factors achieve their required level; one factor (Test conditions, required level 4, achieved level 3) falls short due to the single loading rate tested. This shortfall is offset by the documented rate-independence of the Ti-6Al-4V constitutive response in the 1–10 mm/min range (< 0.5% QoI variation), the comprehensive model form uncertainty analysis, and the conservative acceptance bounds applied. The global sensitivity analysis confirms that the dominant uncertainty sources are material property variability (yield strength, Young's modulus) and friction coefficient, all of which are characterized from lot-specific measurements. The provenance chain from raw experimental data through validation comparison to this decision record is complete and traceable. The credibility evidence package is sufficient to support the regulatory submission claim that the FEA framework reproduces ASTM F1717 compression-bending behavior within pre-established bounds.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z",
    "hasOffsetRationale": {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/decision/cou1-noncannulated-offset-test-conditions",
      "type": "OffsetRationale",
      "refersToFactor": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/cf/test-conditions",
      "justification": "The Test conditions factor achieves level 3 against a required level of 4 because validation testing was conducted at a single crosshead displacement rate (5 mm/min) rather than the ≥2 rates required at MRL 5. This shortfall is offset by three converging lines of evidence: (1) a rate-independence analysis using the calibrated constitutive model demonstrates < 0.5% variation in all three QoIs across the 1–10 mm/min range relevant to ASTM F1717 testing; (2) the global Sobol' sensitivity analysis assigns negligible sensitivity index to loading rate (S1 < 0.01) confirming it is not a dominant uncertainty source; and (3) published literature (Reilly & Burstein, J Biomech 1975; Turner & Burr, Bone 1993) confirms quasi-static rate-independence of metallic implant constructs in this displacement rate regime. The combination of analytical justification, sensitivity analysis, and literature support is judged sufficient to compensate for the missing second loading rate condition, and the overall credibility of the package is not materially diminished."
    }
  },
